# Step 4: Distribution of Variables
numeric_cols <- names(numeric_data)
for(col in numeric_cols) {
  p <- ggplot(depression, aes_string(x=col)) + 
    geom_histogram(binwidth=1, fill="blue", color="black") + 
    theme_minimal()
  print(p)   # printing inside loop
}
## Warning: `aes_string()` was deprecated in ggplot2 3.0.0.

# Step 5: Boxplots
for(col in numeric_cols) {
  p <- ggplot(depression, aes_string(y=col)) + 
    geom_boxplot(fill="orange") + 
    theme_minimal()
  print(p)   # printing inside loop
}

# Step 6: Decide on Logistic Regression Model
library(car)
initial_model <- glm(Depression ~ ., data=depression, family="binomial")
vif(initial_model)
##                 id                Age  Academic.Pressure      Work.Pressure 
##           1.000451           1.024537           1.031257           2.135976 
##               CGPA Study.Satisfaction   Job.Satisfaction   Work.Study.Hours 
##           1.008596           1.006075           2.136827           1.011284
# Step 7: Build Logistic Regression Model with Stepwise Selection
library(MASS)
final_model <- stepAIC(initial_model, direction="both")

# Step 8: Model Diagnostics
library(pscl)
pseudo_r2 <- pR2(final_model)
## fitting null model for pseudo-r2
print(pseudo_r2)
##           llh       llhNull            G2      McFadden          r2ML 
## -1.415295e+04 -1.892957e+04  9.553242e+03  2.523364e-01  2.899343e-01 
##          r2CU 
##  3.904603e-01
vif(final_model)
##                Age  Academic.Pressure               CGPA Study.Satisfaction 
##           1.024508           1.030482           1.005214           1.005416 
##   Work.Study.Hours 
##           1.011179
# Step 9: Check Linearity Assumption
probabilities <- predict(final_model, type="response")
logit <- log(probabilities/(1-probabilities))
for(col in numeric_cols){
  plot(depression[[col]], logit, main=paste("Linearity Check:", col), xlab=col, ylab="Logit")
}
